Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.900 --> 00:00:02.150
DIANE SOLINGER: Hi, everybody.

00:00:02.150 --> 00:00:02.970
I'm Diane Solinger.

00:00:02.970 --> 00:00:04.761
I'm the Manager of the
Googler's Give team.

00:00:04.761 --> 00:00:07.480
We're the team in Google
in People Operations

00:00:07.480 --> 00:00:10.800
that helps Googlers volunteer
and give to charitable causes

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:15.140
and impact issues
that they care about,

00:00:15.140 --> 00:00:17.890
whether it's in their back
yard, around the world.

00:00:17.890 --> 00:00:21.460
And today is World Food Day.

00:00:21.460 --> 00:00:24.810
It's a day that is focused,
obviously, on food,

00:00:24.810 --> 00:00:28.280
but it's really focused in a lot
of ways on the absence of food.

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:33.560
And that's why today is
also launching our team,

00:00:33.560 --> 00:00:35.430
Googlers Give and the
[INAUDIBLE] food team

00:00:35.430 --> 00:00:38.650
are launching the
Hunger Relief campaign.

00:00:38.650 --> 00:00:40.400
This campaign is
in its third year.

00:00:40.400 --> 00:00:43.660
We're pretty excited to work
in partnership with our food

00:00:43.660 --> 00:00:45.950
team that is all
about food, to try

00:00:45.950 --> 00:00:47.850
to help people that
don't have food,

00:00:47.850 --> 00:00:50.530
and particular focus
on children who

00:00:50.530 --> 00:00:52.582
are on the brink of starvation.

00:00:52.582 --> 00:00:55.110
Today it's talking
a little bit more

00:00:55.110 --> 00:00:59.764
about the global picture of
hunger and hunger relief,

00:00:59.764 --> 00:01:01.930
but also about what's
happening in our own community

00:01:01.930 --> 00:01:04.870
here in the Bay area where
Google is headquartered.

00:01:04.870 --> 00:01:08.290
We're really fortunate
to have representatives

00:01:08.290 --> 00:01:11.500
from Stop Hunger Now, which has
been a great partner for Google

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:12.252
and Googlers.

00:01:12.252 --> 00:01:14.460
Many Googlers have been
volunteering with Stop Hunger

00:01:14.460 --> 00:01:17.310
Now over the course
of the past two years.

00:01:17.310 --> 00:01:20.300
And we've been
volunteering to pack food,

00:01:20.300 --> 00:01:23.000
like this, which we'll
show you later, and send

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:25.370
to schools and
children, particularly

00:01:25.370 --> 00:01:29.350
around the world who are really
not getting the nutrition

00:01:29.350 --> 00:01:30.540
that they need.

00:01:30.540 --> 00:01:33.200
Their model is unique,
and Rod will tell us

00:01:33.200 --> 00:01:34.640
a little bit about that.

00:01:34.640 --> 00:01:37.430
We also have the Second Harvest
Food Bank with us today,

00:01:37.430 --> 00:01:39.100
which has been a
partner of Google

00:01:39.100 --> 00:01:40.757
for a very, very long time.

00:01:40.757 --> 00:01:43.090
Many of you know Alan Eustace,
our Senior Vice President

00:01:43.090 --> 00:01:43.790
of Knowledge.

00:01:43.790 --> 00:01:46.620
He works very closely,
annually, with the food bank

00:01:46.620 --> 00:01:51.100
to do a very fun extravaganza
at Costco in Mountain View.

00:01:51.100 --> 00:01:53.870
And that event just keeps
getting bigger and bigger.

00:01:53.870 --> 00:01:56.709
And what we've seen not just
with the Second Harvest Food

00:01:56.709 --> 00:01:58.500
Bank, but with food
banks around the world,

00:01:58.500 --> 00:01:59.916
Googlers are getting
more involved

00:01:59.916 --> 00:02:02.750
in trying to help their local
communities with food security

00:02:02.750 --> 00:02:05.250
issues for people
in their hometowns.

00:02:05.250 --> 00:02:09.930
So we're going to start with a
bit of an overview, World Food

00:02:09.930 --> 00:02:11.900
Day, what's the
landscape out there

00:02:11.900 --> 00:02:15.710
and what is the face of hunger,
and it looks very different

00:02:15.710 --> 00:02:18.800
depending on where
you live in the world.

00:02:18.800 --> 00:02:20.840
If you are in
Nicaragua, which we'll

00:02:20.840 --> 00:02:24.240
hear from Eddy and Jennifer
about their experiences

00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:26.580
in Nicaragua, it's going to
look very different to maybe

00:02:26.580 --> 00:02:28.815
what it looks like
here in East Palo

00:02:28.815 --> 00:02:31.030
Alto or the East
side of San Jose.

00:02:31.030 --> 00:02:32.690
But hunger is real.

00:02:32.690 --> 00:02:36.730
There are over
800 million people

00:02:36.730 --> 00:02:38.830
in the world that don't
get enough to eat.

00:02:38.830 --> 00:02:41.540
And yet, we know there's
enough food for everybody.

00:02:41.540 --> 00:02:44.470
We're just not
getting it to people.

00:02:44.470 --> 00:02:45.990
You think of climate
change and how

00:02:45.990 --> 00:02:48.910
that's affecting the ability for
people to grow crops in the way

00:02:48.910 --> 00:02:49.760
that they used to.

00:02:49.760 --> 00:02:51.718
And we were just talking
about even the drought

00:02:51.718 --> 00:02:52.710
here in California.

00:02:52.710 --> 00:02:55.190
We've got to think
about how we farm

00:02:55.190 --> 00:02:57.710
and what our natural
resources are going to be like

00:02:57.710 --> 00:02:59.470
as climate change affects that.

00:02:59.470 --> 00:03:01.730
So what does that mean
to the small farmer who

00:03:01.730 --> 00:03:03.690
is reliant on just
rainfall and doesn't

00:03:03.690 --> 00:03:06.380
have the systems in place
to get water to their farms?

00:03:06.380 --> 00:03:08.250
And how does that
trickle down, literally,

00:03:08.250 --> 00:03:10.130
to their families
and their children?

00:03:10.130 --> 00:03:12.370
And then what does
that mean systemically

00:03:12.370 --> 00:03:16.830
for kids that don't have
nutrition, whether it's

00:03:16.830 --> 00:03:21.500
in a local school or in
Nicaragua and can't learn?

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:22.420
What happens then?

00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:27.060
So food is the basic need--
food, water, shelter.

00:03:27.060 --> 00:03:30.500
Think about the basic thing
that people need, we need food.

00:03:30.500 --> 00:03:32.930
And not enough people
are getting the food

00:03:32.930 --> 00:03:35.630
that we actually currently have,
and then in the future what

00:03:35.630 --> 00:03:38.480
is that going to look like
when climate change affects us,

00:03:38.480 --> 00:03:41.880
or other instances that
we can't even predict.

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:43.750
But food is a basic
need, and that's

00:03:43.750 --> 00:03:45.250
what World Food Day is about.

00:03:45.250 --> 00:03:47.250
That's what the Hunger
Relief Campaign is about.

00:03:47.250 --> 00:03:50.000
And that's what these two
great organizations are about.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.260
So I'm going to kick it
over to Rod Brooks who's

00:03:53.260 --> 00:03:55.080
the CEO of Stop Hunger Now.

00:03:55.080 --> 00:03:57.100
It's based in North
Carolina, but the history

00:03:57.100 --> 00:03:59.584
of this organization
is pretty fascinating.

00:03:59.584 --> 00:04:02.000
And as you'll notice with both
these organizations, Second

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.030
Harvest and Stop Hunger
Now, there's a plate

00:04:04.030 --> 00:04:07.540
and there's some utensils
around both of their logos.

00:04:07.540 --> 00:04:11.280
So it's [INAUDIBLE] let's
get that food in you.

00:04:11.280 --> 00:04:13.710
But the history of Stop Hunger
Now is really interesting

00:04:13.710 --> 00:04:16.010
because food banking
was a part of it.

00:04:16.010 --> 00:04:17.899
But then where you've
evolved, and just

00:04:17.899 --> 00:04:19.769
give us the high level
scope of the view

00:04:19.769 --> 00:04:21.410
that you have with
your organization

00:04:21.410 --> 00:04:22.419
on the hunger issue.

00:04:22.419 --> 00:04:23.210
ROD BROOKS: I will.

00:04:23.210 --> 00:04:25.047
Well, thank you, Diane,
really, for inviting

00:04:25.047 --> 00:04:27.130
us to be a part of this
event, and for kicking off

00:04:27.130 --> 00:04:31.000
this hunger campaign that
you're initiating today.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.370
As we get started here, I
want to invite everyone just

00:04:33.370 --> 00:04:35.910
to let you know that we will
be entertaining your questions.

00:04:35.910 --> 00:04:38.160
So we have some things
to share with you today,

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:40.284
but really we're hoping
this can be a conversation.

00:04:40.284 --> 00:04:41.650
We invite your questions.

00:04:41.650 --> 00:04:44.750
So be thinking
about what you might

00:04:44.750 --> 00:04:46.570
ask at the end of
our presentation.

00:04:46.570 --> 00:04:50.737
But I wanted to start to
just first by giving you

00:04:50.737 --> 00:04:52.820
some more information sort
of from the global view

00:04:52.820 --> 00:04:55.430
about world hunger.

00:04:55.430 --> 00:04:58.020
Diane just shared some
information with you.

00:04:58.020 --> 00:05:01.630
Right now there are, in
fact, 805 million people

00:05:01.630 --> 00:05:04.080
around the world who
are malnourished,

00:05:04.080 --> 00:05:06.420
who suffer from hunger
on a daily basis.

00:05:06.420 --> 00:05:08.360
That's one in every nine of us.

00:05:08.360 --> 00:05:09.530
Now, think about it.

00:05:09.530 --> 00:05:13.440
If one in nine of
us in this room

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:15.630
were malnourished, didn't
have the food they need,

00:05:15.630 --> 00:05:17.690
would there be any
other priority?

00:05:17.690 --> 00:05:19.065
Would there be
any other priority

00:05:19.065 --> 00:05:22.840
than making sure that
those individuals had food.

00:05:22.840 --> 00:05:25.645
That's a question we
have to ask ourselves.

00:05:25.645 --> 00:05:28.480
Of the 805 million
that suffer from hunger

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:31.840
every single day,
about 25,000 a day

00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:36.380
die from hunger and
hunger-related causes.

00:05:36.380 --> 00:05:38.970
That number is astounding to me.

00:05:38.970 --> 00:05:40.559
Particularly, as you
mentioned, Diane,

00:05:40.559 --> 00:05:42.100
when there's enough
food in the world

00:05:42.100 --> 00:05:43.850
to feed every single person.

00:05:43.850 --> 00:05:46.890
40% of those suffering
from hunger are children.

00:05:46.890 --> 00:05:50.760
Why is it that children
have to die every single day

00:05:50.760 --> 00:05:52.510
from the lack of
food when there's

00:05:52.510 --> 00:05:55.260
enough food to feed everyone.

00:05:55.260 --> 00:05:59.590
That is really why we're having
this conversation here today.

00:05:59.590 --> 00:06:02.530
As we think about
those numbers, it's

00:06:02.530 --> 00:06:05.020
easy to get depressed
or a little more

00:06:05.020 --> 00:06:07.460
than challenged, frankly,
overwhelmed sometimes.

00:06:07.460 --> 00:06:10.397
But there's actually some good
news to share around these,

00:06:10.397 --> 00:06:11.980
and that is in the
progress that we're

00:06:11.980 --> 00:06:13.840
making towards ending hunger.

00:06:13.840 --> 00:06:16.370
So the United Nations
just recently announced

00:06:16.370 --> 00:06:19.542
its annual Hunger State
of Food Insecurity Report,

00:06:19.542 --> 00:06:21.250
and there's good news,
actually, to share

00:06:21.250 --> 00:06:23.840
in the progress we're making
towards ending hunger.

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:27.730
What that report showed
was that that 805 million

00:06:27.730 --> 00:06:29.670
who suffer from hunger
today is actually

00:06:29.670 --> 00:06:33.730
100 million people less
than the number that

00:06:33.730 --> 00:06:36.150
suffered from
hunger 10 years ago.

00:06:36.150 --> 00:06:38.280
So in one decade we've
reduced the number

00:06:38.280 --> 00:06:41.550
of malnourished people in the
world by 100 million people.

00:06:41.550 --> 00:06:45.070
If you go back further than
that, we've actually since 1992

00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:48.670
we've reduced the number
of malnourished people

00:06:48.670 --> 00:06:51.420
by more than 200 million people.

00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:52.210
That's remarkable.

00:06:52.210 --> 00:06:54.616
Especially when you think
about the population growth

00:06:54.616 --> 00:06:55.990
that we've seen
during that time.

00:06:55.990 --> 00:06:58.930
So when you look at the
prevalence of hunger

00:06:58.930 --> 00:07:03.210
around the world, you actually
see that in 1992 there

00:07:03.210 --> 00:07:06.200
were just under
19% of the world's

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:09.800
population were malnourished.

00:07:09.800 --> 00:07:12.530
Because of the advances, the
progress that we've seen,

00:07:12.530 --> 00:07:16.890
that percentage is just
over 11% now, 11.3%.

00:07:16.890 --> 00:07:18.640
That's remarkable
progress, and truly it's

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:20.310
something to give us hope.

00:07:20.310 --> 00:07:23.140
We have 63 countries
that have actually

00:07:23.140 --> 00:07:25.760
met the first Millennium
development goal.

00:07:25.760 --> 00:07:29.390
That was to cut hunger
in half by the year 2015.

00:07:29.390 --> 00:07:32.300
63 countries that have
already made that happen.

00:07:32.300 --> 00:07:35.160
That gives us hope, in fact,
that we can do that worldwide.

00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:37.910
We can meet that first
Millennium development goal

00:07:37.910 --> 00:07:40.020
worldwide by 2015.

00:07:40.020 --> 00:07:41.635
We have the
opportunity to do that.

00:07:41.635 --> 00:07:44.110
That goal is within reach.

00:07:44.110 --> 00:07:48.110
It will take some extra work,
because we're reducing hunger

00:07:48.110 --> 00:07:51.672
at the rate of about half a
percentage point per year.

00:07:51.672 --> 00:07:53.630
So we need to step up
our efforts a little bit,

00:07:53.630 --> 00:07:56.560
but that goal is very
much within reach.

00:07:56.560 --> 00:07:58.824
So there's good news,
but while there's

00:07:58.824 --> 00:08:00.240
good news in the
progress, we need

00:08:00.240 --> 00:08:02.340
to understand what's
making that possible,

00:08:02.340 --> 00:08:06.200
and we need to not lose
focus because hunger

00:08:06.200 --> 00:08:07.690
is a very local issue.

00:08:07.690 --> 00:08:10.190
And I think you'll hear
that today, that hunger is

00:08:10.190 --> 00:08:12.740
a very local issue,
and in some cases,

00:08:12.740 --> 00:08:14.590
the numbers aren't
getting better.

00:08:14.590 --> 00:08:16.596
So we need to learn from
what we've done well

00:08:16.596 --> 00:08:17.970
in the successes
that we've seen,

00:08:17.970 --> 00:08:21.090
but we have to keep that at
focus and that commitment

00:08:21.090 --> 00:08:23.850
to actually ending
hunger in our lifetime.

00:08:23.850 --> 00:08:28.510
So I will just share briefly
what Stop Hunger Now is doing.

00:08:28.510 --> 00:08:31.950
In fact, our roots do come
from domestic hunger relief.

00:08:31.950 --> 00:08:35.480
Our Founder Ray
Buchanan helped found

00:08:35.480 --> 00:08:38.039
the Society of St. Andrew, which
was one of the original meal

00:08:38.039 --> 00:08:40.140
gleaning organizations.

00:08:40.140 --> 00:08:44.800
But in 1998, his focus
turned international

00:08:44.800 --> 00:08:47.350
as he realized the need to
address international hunger

00:08:47.350 --> 00:08:49.130
relief.

00:08:49.130 --> 00:08:52.540
Initially our focus
was on crisis response.

00:08:52.540 --> 00:08:55.180
But very quickly you
learn that the disasters

00:08:55.180 --> 00:08:58.140
that we read about-- the
earthquakes, the tsunamis,

00:08:58.140 --> 00:09:00.300
the famine brought about
by war, et cetera-- that's

00:09:00.300 --> 00:09:01.840
only a small portion
of the hunger that

00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:02.673
exists in the world.

00:09:02.673 --> 00:09:04.210
In fact, the real
need is to address

00:09:04.210 --> 00:09:07.370
the chronic malnutrition
that exists.

00:09:07.370 --> 00:09:12.180
And so what Stop Hunger
Now began doing around 2005

00:09:12.180 --> 00:09:14.440
was working to address
chronic malnutrition.

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:17.150
And we learned that one
of the most effective ways

00:09:17.150 --> 00:09:19.930
to address chronic malnutrition
in developing countries

00:09:19.930 --> 00:09:23.430
is school feeding programs.

00:09:23.430 --> 00:09:26.910
So we initiated a
meal packaging program

00:09:26.910 --> 00:09:29.800
where volunteers, like the many
Googlers who have participated

00:09:29.800 --> 00:09:33.220
with us, they come together
and package these high protein

00:09:33.220 --> 00:09:34.210
dehydrated meals.

00:09:34.210 --> 00:09:37.700
These meals have rice,
soy, dehydrated vegetables,

00:09:37.700 --> 00:09:41.654
and a specially formulated
vitamin formulation

00:09:41.654 --> 00:09:43.570
that is designed for
malnourished individuals,

00:09:43.570 --> 00:09:45.278
to give them the
micronutrients that they

00:09:45.278 --> 00:09:47.730
need to overcome the
effects of hunger.

00:09:47.730 --> 00:09:50.120
So volunteers come together
and package these meals.

00:09:50.120 --> 00:09:52.860
Then we provide
them to partners--

00:09:52.860 --> 00:09:56.980
we work with partners in
more than 40 countries now.

00:09:56.980 --> 00:10:01.750
And to date, we're serving
about 400,000 people a day

00:10:01.750 --> 00:10:04.217
using our meals.

00:10:04.217 --> 00:10:05.800
DIANE SOLINGER: The
distribution model

00:10:05.800 --> 00:10:08.490
of the schools I think
is really, really

00:10:08.490 --> 00:10:11.786
a special thing that you
guys do extraordinarily well.

00:10:11.786 --> 00:10:13.410
ROD BROOKS: Well,
and that's the issue.

00:10:13.410 --> 00:10:15.826
There are many ways that these
meals could be distributed.

00:10:15.826 --> 00:10:18.030
What we're trying to do
is to really leverage

00:10:18.030 --> 00:10:19.880
the distribution that
we have, to provide

00:10:19.880 --> 00:10:23.077
not only an immediate impact,
but really a long term impact.

00:10:23.077 --> 00:10:24.410
Now, let me say more about that.

00:10:24.410 --> 00:10:26.618
So of course, when you start
a school feeding program

00:10:26.618 --> 00:10:29.490
you're providing
the immediate immed

00:10:29.490 --> 00:10:31.850
that children need, to learn.

00:10:31.850 --> 00:10:34.350
You'll hear in a moment how
it's really impossible to learn.

00:10:34.350 --> 00:10:37.810
You can't think, concentrate,
on an empty belly.

00:10:37.810 --> 00:10:41.260
But also what we find is when we
start a school feeding program,

00:10:41.260 --> 00:10:43.950
those meals act is a
tremendous incentive

00:10:43.950 --> 00:10:46.570
for parents to send their
children to school, knowing

00:10:46.570 --> 00:10:48.070
that they'll get a hot meal.

00:10:48.070 --> 00:10:51.240
What does that do, as school
enrollment rates increase

00:10:51.240 --> 00:10:53.090
dramatically--
sometimes we've seen

00:10:53.090 --> 00:10:57.550
double, triple, quadruple or
more-- literacy rates increase.

00:10:57.550 --> 00:11:00.110
Vocational training
opportunities are present.

00:11:00.110 --> 00:11:03.856
Through that education,
children have hope.

00:11:03.856 --> 00:11:05.480
And it's through that
education that we

00:11:05.480 --> 00:11:07.940
can begin to break the
cycle of poverty that

00:11:07.940 --> 00:11:09.664
so often keeps
hunger in existence.

