00:11:42.497 --> 00:11:44.580
Is it going to help meet
that goal of getting kids

00:11:44.580 --> 00:11:47.660
to have six years of
education, of formal education?

00:11:47.660 --> 00:11:48.410
EDDY MORALES: Yes.

00:11:48.410 --> 00:11:49.090
That's right.

00:11:49.090 --> 00:11:51.870
Thank you for inviting
us, also, from Nicaragua.

00:11:51.870 --> 00:11:53.820
It's so good to be
here and to share

00:11:53.820 --> 00:11:57.260
what we're doing in Nicaragua
and how things are changing.

00:11:57.260 --> 00:11:59.240
So for Jennifer,
Leyla and myself,

00:11:59.240 --> 00:12:00.905
it's so exciting to be here.

00:12:00.905 --> 00:12:01.720
And yes.

00:12:01.720 --> 00:12:04.240
And then personally
work with them

00:12:04.240 --> 00:12:06.220
with a school feeding program.

00:12:06.220 --> 00:12:10.910
I remember when I started, we
were feeding 56,000 children,

00:12:10.910 --> 00:12:13.550
and grow the program up to one
million children every day.

00:12:13.550 --> 00:12:14.550
DIANE SOLINGER:
That's incredible.

00:12:14.550 --> 00:12:15.050
Wow.

00:12:15.050 --> 00:12:17.950
EDDY MORALES: And the big thing
there was more than growing

00:12:17.950 --> 00:12:20.680
the number is creating
hope for these children,

00:12:20.680 --> 00:12:23.610
creating opportunities
for these children

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:26.587
for a way of broken
cycles of poverty,

00:12:26.587 --> 00:12:28.045
knowing the life
of these children.

00:12:28.045 --> 00:12:31.862
And yes, when the parents know
that there is no foot home,

00:12:31.862 --> 00:12:33.570
but at the school
there is food, and then

00:12:33.570 --> 00:12:35.770
teachers can take
advantage of that,

00:12:35.770 --> 00:12:37.400
know to then work
with the children

00:12:37.400 --> 00:12:39.660
in the field of
education, that's amazing.

00:12:39.660 --> 00:12:41.475
And that is happening
in Nicaragua.

00:12:41.475 --> 00:12:45.790
And today we are serving
with our partners.

00:12:45.790 --> 00:12:50.760
We are serving 18,000
children in Nicaragua.

00:12:50.760 --> 00:12:53.790
And one of the big indicators
that we're working on

00:12:53.790 --> 00:12:54.530
is education.

00:12:54.530 --> 00:12:57.240
So we really want our
kids to go to school.

00:12:57.240 --> 00:12:58.500
It's more than the meal.

00:12:58.500 --> 00:13:02.870
The meal is a way of probably
bringing hope and telling them

00:13:02.870 --> 00:13:03.770
yes, it's possible.

00:13:03.770 --> 00:13:05.320
Yes, we can make it happen.

00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:06.590
Yes, we're going to feed you.

00:13:06.590 --> 00:13:09.900
There will be a meal, but what
we want you to go to school.

00:13:09.900 --> 00:13:12.390
Because at the end of the
day, what is going to make

00:13:12.390 --> 00:13:15.480
a difference in their life
is not the meal itself,

00:13:15.480 --> 00:13:17.830
but including education to that.

00:13:17.830 --> 00:13:19.670
And actually, that's our story.

00:13:19.670 --> 00:13:22.470
Leyla, myself, and
me, that's our story.

00:13:22.470 --> 00:13:25.100
Education is what change
our life, what took us out

00:13:25.100 --> 00:13:26.110
of poverty.

00:13:26.110 --> 00:13:28.730
DIANE SOLINGER: Before we go
to Jennifer who has that story,

00:13:28.730 --> 00:13:32.850
how did you guys find
each other as partners?

00:13:32.850 --> 00:13:33.680
ROD BROOKS: Well--

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:34.350
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:34.350 --> 00:13:35.600
DIANE SOLINGER: Do you Google?

00:13:35.600 --> 00:13:38.490
Did you Google it?

00:13:38.490 --> 00:13:40.700
ROD BROOKS: So we
initiated our program

00:13:40.700 --> 00:13:43.070
and we had been working
with a number of partners

00:13:43.070 --> 00:13:46.090
around the world
providing crisis response,

00:13:46.090 --> 00:13:49.410
and then as we initiated
the meal packaging program,

00:13:49.410 --> 00:13:52.530
we found that certain partners
who were receiving meals

00:13:52.530 --> 00:13:54.790
from us would refer
other partners.

00:13:54.790 --> 00:13:57.280
Once the meals get out
there, people find you.

00:13:57.280 --> 00:14:00.210
And I think that was the
case with ORPHANetwork.

00:14:00.210 --> 00:14:03.870
It was, in fact, one
of our staff members

00:14:03.870 --> 00:14:06.800
had traveled to Nicaragua
through her church.

00:14:06.800 --> 00:14:08.950
And it was through
Chessney Barrick,

00:14:08.950 --> 00:14:11.417
who had a direct experience
with ORPHANetwork,

00:14:11.417 --> 00:14:13.500
who said, you know, this
is a group that we really

00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:14.550
ought to try to help.

00:14:14.550 --> 00:14:17.800
She was so moved by the work
that Eddy and ORPHANetwork

00:14:17.800 --> 00:14:18.631
was doing.

00:14:18.631 --> 00:14:20.130
And I just have to
brag, by the way.

00:14:20.130 --> 00:14:22.600
When we talk about
ending hunger,

00:14:22.600 --> 00:14:24.060
we're really serious about that.

00:14:24.060 --> 00:14:29.044
And I think ORPHANetwork is
one of the best examples where,

00:14:29.044 --> 00:14:30.460
as Eddy mentioned,
they're feeding

00:14:30.460 --> 00:14:32.530
18,000 children every day.

00:14:32.530 --> 00:14:36.220
Well, in four years, the rate of
malnutrition among those 18,000

00:14:36.220 --> 00:14:41.660
children has dropped from 27%
to 12%-- more than cut in half.

00:14:41.660 --> 00:14:44.140
And that is remarkable.

00:14:44.140 --> 00:14:46.030
EDDY MORALES: And
that's the work

00:14:46.030 --> 00:14:48.750
the churches and partners
and friends and doctors

00:14:48.750 --> 00:14:51.480
and everyone is
doing in Nicaragua.

00:14:51.480 --> 00:14:55.900
We are so focused on result.

00:14:55.900 --> 00:14:58.430
It's sort of
result-based management.

00:14:58.430 --> 00:15:00.210
So we said, man, by
feeding the children

00:15:00.210 --> 00:15:02.001
only we are not going
to make a difference.

00:15:02.001 --> 00:15:04.030
So what if we can work
on some indicators

00:15:04.030 --> 00:15:05.560
and work towards those.

00:15:05.560 --> 00:15:07.490
So one of our indicator
three years ago

00:15:07.490 --> 00:15:09.477
was to wipe out malnutrition.

00:15:09.477 --> 00:15:11.060
And that's what we're
working towards.

00:15:11.060 --> 00:15:12.780
The idea is wipe
out malnutrition.

00:15:12.780 --> 00:15:15.570
We always say every
community we put one step in,

00:15:15.570 --> 00:15:17.880
we want to wipe out
malnutrition while we're

00:15:17.880 --> 00:15:19.860
sending the kids
to school, also.

00:15:19.860 --> 00:15:20.840
DIANE SOLINGER: That's
kind of step one.

00:15:20.840 --> 00:15:21.631
EDDY MORALES: Yeah.

00:15:21.631 --> 00:15:25.520
So the numbers, as Rod said,
number has gone from 26%,

00:15:25.520 --> 00:15:27.000
actually, to 12%.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:30.210
This year we're going to end,
or we're working really hard

00:15:30.210 --> 00:15:32.850
to end this year with 8%.

00:15:32.850 --> 00:15:34.990
And in some communities
it's already

00:15:34.990 --> 00:15:36.846
down to 3%, 2%, and yes.

00:15:36.846 --> 00:15:38.470
DIANE SOLINGER: And
are you distributed

00:15:38.470 --> 00:15:39.820
throughout the country
or are you focused

00:15:39.820 --> 00:15:40.736
strictly in Nicaragua?

00:15:40.736 --> 00:15:47.130
EDDY MORALES: No, we are in
almost 14 states or departments

00:15:47.130 --> 00:15:49.380
out of 18, roughly.

00:15:49.380 --> 00:15:51.171
And the idea is to
reach the country, also.

00:15:51.171 --> 00:15:52.510
DIANE SOLINGER: That's amazing.

00:15:52.510 --> 00:15:55.850
So Jennifer, you've
been a recipient

00:15:55.850 --> 00:15:57.727
of Stop Hunger Now
and ORPHANetwork.

00:15:57.727 --> 00:15:59.560
Tell us about your
story, because now you're

00:15:59.560 --> 00:16:00.470
in university.

00:16:00.470 --> 00:16:01.950
JENNIFER: Yes, I'm a sophomore.

00:16:01.950 --> 00:16:02.290
DIANE SOLINGER: Perfect.

00:16:02.290 --> 00:16:04.581
JENNIFER: Actually, I would
have five years in college,

00:16:04.581 --> 00:16:06.600
so I guess I'll
be a senior twice.

00:16:06.600 --> 00:16:08.420
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:08.420 --> 00:16:14.390
Anyway, I'm 18 years old, and
I was raised in an orphanage.

00:16:14.390 --> 00:16:19.080
My mom-- well, my father left
us when I was three years old,

00:16:19.080 --> 00:16:21.880
and my mom didn't have enough
money to make ends meet.

00:16:21.880 --> 00:16:24.740
So I just learned that
phrase, "ends meet."

00:16:24.740 --> 00:16:26.680
I like it.

00:16:26.680 --> 00:16:29.760
So she put us in the
orphanage because-- me,

00:16:29.760 --> 00:16:32.530
and my brother-- my oldest
brother-- and of course,

00:16:32.530 --> 00:16:34.460
I was destroyed at first.

00:16:34.460 --> 00:16:36.720
I just couldn't understand
why I was in there.

00:16:36.720 --> 00:16:39.000
I mean why?

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:43.110
And at first, I got sick.

00:16:43.110 --> 00:16:44.980
Seeing as I was sick,
I wouldn't eat--

00:16:44.980 --> 00:16:48.790
not that the food was bad,
just that I was so depressed.

00:16:48.790 --> 00:16:50.360
My only consolation
was my brother.

00:16:53.060 --> 00:16:56.330
I just didn't know why
she was leaving us there.

00:16:56.330 --> 00:17:01.560
But then, through time, I got to
understand why was the reason.

00:17:01.560 --> 00:17:06.760
And I got to love the place
because through time, I

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:09.349
thought of the place as my home.

00:17:09.349 --> 00:17:12.369
It's just that it was a
huge home with 80 kids that

00:17:12.369 --> 00:17:14.150
were like my
brother and sisters,

00:17:14.150 --> 00:17:16.300
and my caregivers
were my parents.

00:17:16.300 --> 00:17:22.980
So I got to know that it was in
God's plan for me to be there.

00:17:22.980 --> 00:17:27.200
And to be here with you now,
to be sharing this testimony

00:17:27.200 --> 00:17:31.860
with you, because it
was awesome, seriously.

00:17:31.860 --> 00:17:38.550
My childhood was as, I
think all the same as you.

00:17:38.550 --> 00:17:39.700
I got to play a lot.

00:17:39.700 --> 00:17:42.230
I always have tons of energy.

00:17:42.230 --> 00:17:45.330
And I went to school.

00:17:45.330 --> 00:17:49.060
I had good grades, because
I had good caregivers that

00:17:49.060 --> 00:17:52.270
were always helping me and
were always encouraging me.

00:17:52.270 --> 00:17:54.610
And because they bet on me.

00:17:54.610 --> 00:17:56.660
And when somebody
bet on you, you're

00:17:56.660 --> 00:18:00.390
like how can you
disappoint that person?

00:18:00.390 --> 00:18:01.870
And it's the same
with all of you.

00:18:01.870 --> 00:18:04.710
You have bet on us,
because you're working,

00:18:04.710 --> 00:18:09.160
you are helping us, you're
willing to do something for us.

00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:12.590
Like hunger, the Stop
Hunger Now and ORPHANetwork,

00:18:12.590 --> 00:18:14.150
they bet on us.

00:18:14.150 --> 00:18:16.530
And that's encouraging,
because you say,

00:18:16.530 --> 00:18:20.330
wow, these people
are not my parents,

00:18:20.330 --> 00:18:22.510
that didn't know
anything about me

00:18:22.510 --> 00:18:23.870
went I arrive at the orphanage.

00:18:23.870 --> 00:18:24.970
They welcome me.

00:18:24.970 --> 00:18:26.180
They hug me, they kiss me.

00:18:26.180 --> 00:18:27.870
They treat me as
their own child.

00:18:30.460 --> 00:18:31.980
And when you see
all that, you want

00:18:31.980 --> 00:18:34.400
to do that, you want
to be part of that.

00:18:34.400 --> 00:18:39.380
You want to be
someone like Eddy.

00:18:39.380 --> 00:18:41.750
I still think that I want
to take your position.

00:18:41.750 --> 00:18:44.025
I want to continue
that legacy, you know.

00:18:44.025 --> 00:18:47.560
I want to keep working
with child-- I love childs.

00:18:47.560 --> 00:18:49.950
Although sometimes
they drive me crazy.

00:18:49.950 --> 00:18:53.440
I just love to be
with childs and youth,

00:18:53.440 --> 00:18:58.490
and to be able to be there
for them as all of you

00:18:58.490 --> 00:18:59.710
have been there for me.

00:18:59.710 --> 00:19:04.580
Because I think of all
of you as my family.

00:19:04.580 --> 00:19:06.320
When I arrived at
the orphanage, I

00:19:06.320 --> 00:19:09.340
was like only my brother--
brother come here, please.

00:19:09.340 --> 00:19:10.260
Be with me.

00:19:10.260 --> 00:19:12.770
But then I have
now many friends.

00:19:12.770 --> 00:19:14.860
I mean tons of friends in there.

00:19:14.860 --> 00:19:19.300
And it was great
to experience that.

00:19:19.300 --> 00:19:24.830
It was great to have home
and roof, food to eat.

00:19:24.830 --> 00:19:29.750
Because when you don't have
food, and you go to school,

00:19:29.750 --> 00:19:34.830
you're like going on empty
stomach, you can't think,

00:19:34.830 --> 00:19:35.950
you can't reason.

00:19:35.950 --> 00:19:38.819
You probably have bad
grades because you

00:19:38.819 --> 00:19:40.360
don't have something
in your stomach.

00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:43.080
And it's, oh, my
gosh, I'm so hungry.

00:19:43.080 --> 00:19:44.740
You cannot think
about anything else.

00:19:44.740 --> 00:19:48.210
But I was glad I had food.

00:19:48.210 --> 00:19:50.400
I remember I was telling
someone yesterday

00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:56.480
that one time, when I was
maybe 10 or 11, the caregivers

00:19:56.480 --> 00:19:57.980
were going to fast.

00:19:57.980 --> 00:20:00.670
And I said, OK, I
want to do that, too.

00:20:00.670 --> 00:20:02.650
And they say, OK, do
know what is that?

00:20:02.650 --> 00:20:04.350
I was like, no.

00:20:04.350 --> 00:20:07.070
And then they explain
what in was to me.

00:20:07.070 --> 00:20:08.280
I say, OK, wait.

00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:09.180
We pray to God.

00:20:09.180 --> 00:20:11.320
We don't eat all
day until dinner.

00:20:11.320 --> 00:20:12.990
I say, OK, I'm going to do that.

00:20:12.990 --> 00:20:14.390
I have a reason to do it.

00:20:14.390 --> 00:20:18.955
But after school, I
came to the orphanage

00:20:18.955 --> 00:20:22.325
and I was crying and crying,
and my brother came to me.

00:20:22.325 --> 00:20:23.860
He was like, what's the matter?

00:20:23.860 --> 00:20:24.990
What's up?

00:20:24.990 --> 00:20:28.220
I was like, I'm
so hungry, I said.

00:20:28.220 --> 00:20:30.050
And he say, well, go eat.

00:20:30.050 --> 00:20:30.720
I said I can't.

00:20:30.720 --> 00:20:33.320
I'm fasting.

00:20:33.320 --> 00:20:34.630
And he said, don't be crazy.

00:20:34.630 --> 00:20:36.300
God will understand you.

00:20:36.300 --> 00:20:39.370
He knows what you need.

00:20:39.370 --> 00:20:40.660
I was like, wow.

00:20:40.660 --> 00:20:44.560
I mean any other
person could say, well,

00:20:44.560 --> 00:20:46.960
I don't have nowhere
to go to eat.

00:20:46.960 --> 00:20:47.780
But I did.

00:20:47.780 --> 00:20:50.930
I knew that I could
go to the kitchen

00:20:50.930 --> 00:20:54.000
and ask the cookers to
give me something to eat.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:55.940
I was like, wow, this is great.

00:20:55.940 --> 00:20:58.430
I felt very lucky to be there.

00:20:58.430 --> 00:21:01.230
DIANE SOLINGER: Just like we
were all saying, it's step one.

00:21:01.230 --> 00:21:02.280
JENNIFER: Exactly.

00:21:02.280 --> 00:21:04.571
DIANE SOLINGER: Making sure
that there's food security.

00:21:04.571 --> 00:21:08.550
And for us who pack these
wonderful packages of food

00:21:08.550 --> 00:21:11.350
and ship them off to we don't
know where sometimes, it's

00:21:11.350 --> 00:21:15.330
really nice to see that it
gets from you to you to you,

00:21:15.330 --> 00:21:18.640
and now you're thinking
about-- as I said earlier,

00:21:18.640 --> 00:21:19.410
paying it forward.

00:21:19.410 --> 00:21:21.035
You're going to go
back and try to help

00:21:21.035 --> 00:21:23.050
and I think that's
a wonderful circle.

00:21:23.050 --> 00:21:24.120
Thank you.

00:21:24.120 --> 00:21:28.545
And food security,
that term, it's

00:21:28.545 --> 00:21:30.420
an issue here in the Bay area.

00:21:30.420 --> 00:21:32.890
It's an issue in
the developed world.

00:21:32.890 --> 00:21:36.810
And we talk about children
going to school hungry

00:21:36.810 --> 00:21:40.130
here in the Bay area, and that's
just not acceptable anywhere.

00:21:40.130 --> 00:21:43.020
So Kathy, tell us about
Second Harvest Mission.

00:21:43.020 --> 00:21:45.464
What you do for the
counties that you support,

00:21:45.464 --> 00:21:47.630
and overall food banking,
if people don't understand

00:21:47.630 --> 00:21:49.179
even the concept of that maybe.

00:21:49.179 --> 00:21:50.220
KATHY JACKSON: OK, great.

00:21:50.220 --> 00:21:53.220
Well, I want you guys to
know that the only reason I'm

00:21:53.220 --> 00:21:56.810
wearing logo-wear instead
of my Buster Posey Jersey

00:21:56.810 --> 00:22:00.230
is because I knew I was
going to be on camera,

00:22:00.230 --> 00:22:03.400
and I didn't want to
preserve for the ages.

00:22:03.400 --> 00:22:07.090
But I would like to
talk about three things.

00:22:07.090 --> 00:22:11.470
I'd like to talk a little bit
about the business of hunger.

00:22:11.470 --> 00:22:14.000
I want to talk a little bit
about what hunger looks like

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:16.340
here in Silicon Valley.

00:22:16.340 --> 00:22:18.090
And I want to talk a
little bit about what

00:22:18.090 --> 00:22:19.796
Second Harvest is
doing about it, OK?

00:22:19.796 --> 00:22:21.410
DIANE SOLINGER: Sounds good.

00:22:21.410 --> 00:22:23.830
KATHY JACKSON: So why
would I use a weird phrase

00:22:23.830 --> 00:22:25.490
like the business of hunger?

00:22:25.490 --> 00:22:27.640
The reason I refer
to it that way

00:22:27.640 --> 00:22:32.250
is that we're all about data
at Second Harvest Food Bank.

00:22:32.250 --> 00:22:34.010
We're focused on data.

00:22:34.010 --> 00:22:35.600
We're focused on metrics.

00:22:35.600 --> 00:22:37.590
We're focused on efficiency.

00:22:37.590 --> 00:22:40.650
I came to this work after
20 years in for-profit,

00:22:40.650 --> 00:22:45.650
and I don't know any other way
to run a business, honestly.

00:22:45.650 --> 00:22:48.920
So when we start looking at our
two counties, and we serve--

00:22:48.920 --> 00:22:51.350
we're the only food bank in
Santa Clara and San Mateo

00:22:51.350 --> 00:22:52.010
county.

00:22:52.010 --> 00:22:53.890
Food banking is not
a competitive sport.

00:22:53.890 --> 00:22:56.150
We're not competing
with anybody.

00:22:56.150 --> 00:22:59.280
But when we start looking at
where the pockets of hunger

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:00.880
are, we start with income.

00:23:00.880 --> 00:23:05.570
And the State of California
says that a family of four

00:23:05.570 --> 00:23:10.580
needs $82,000 here
to make ends meet.

00:23:10.580 --> 00:23:14.050
84% of our clients are
getting by on a household

00:23:14.050 --> 00:23:16.290
income of $20,000 or less.

00:23:16.290 --> 00:23:19.800
So try to imagine living on
something like $15,000 here.

00:23:19.800 --> 00:23:21.480
I mean it blows
your mind, really.

00:23:21.480 --> 00:23:23.680
I don't know how people do it.

00:23:23.680 --> 00:23:27.650
But we start, we map where
the pockets of low income are.

00:23:27.650 --> 00:23:29.760
And then we overlay on that.

00:23:29.760 --> 00:23:34.480
We overlay all of
our 330 partners,

00:23:34.480 --> 00:23:38.540
and 770 different food
distribution points.

00:23:38.540 --> 00:23:41.640
We overlay on that our
particularly strong partners

00:23:41.640 --> 00:23:43.980
who could grow and
help us do more.

00:23:43.980 --> 00:23:46.870
And we overlay on that
food stamp penetration

00:23:46.870 --> 00:23:50.070
rates, because the more
people utilize food stamps who

00:23:50.070 --> 00:23:51.660
actually qualify
for that program,

00:23:51.660 --> 00:23:53.830
it will leverage our resources.

00:23:53.830 --> 00:23:56.360
And what happens is
then you find gaps.

00:23:56.360 --> 00:23:58.530
You find areas
that are saturated

00:23:58.530 --> 00:24:00.320
in terms of a lot
of food coming in,

00:24:00.320 --> 00:24:01.900
even if there's a lot of need.

00:24:01.900 --> 00:24:04.620
And we use that
analysis to figure out

00:24:04.620 --> 00:24:07.940
where we're going to go,
where we need more services,

00:24:07.940 --> 00:24:10.720
how we maximize our
ROI, how we drive

00:24:10.720 --> 00:24:12.637
impact on this critical problem.

00:24:12.637 --> 00:24:15.220
DIANE SOLINGER: Similar to the
whole thing, even that mapping,

00:24:15.220 --> 00:24:17.400
there's food, it's just
maybe in the wrong places.

00:24:17.400 --> 00:24:18.710
KATHY JACKSON: Exactly.

00:24:18.710 --> 00:24:19.610
Exactly.

00:24:19.610 --> 00:24:23.300
So what does hunger
look like here?

00:24:23.300 --> 00:24:27.260
I suspect you guys see
faces of hunger every day,

00:24:27.260 --> 00:24:30.050
but you probably don't know
it because it looks different

00:24:30.050 --> 00:24:30.850
here.

00:24:30.850 --> 00:24:32.530
Second Harvest Food
Bank provides food

00:24:32.530 --> 00:24:36.550
to a quarter of a million
people every month.

00:24:36.550 --> 00:24:40.500
That's one in 10 people
in these two counties

00:24:40.500 --> 00:24:42.700
get some of their food
from the food bank.

00:24:42.700 --> 00:24:46.100
So they're cafeteria workers.

00:24:46.100 --> 00:24:47.940
They may be preschool teachers.

00:24:47.940 --> 00:24:50.830
They may be somebody who waits
on you in a hardware store.

00:24:50.830 --> 00:24:54.430
If you know an adult that's
trying to live on minimum wage,

00:24:54.430 --> 00:24:58.330
even minimum wage in Mountain
View, which might go to $15,

00:24:58.330 --> 00:25:00.450
that's only a little
over $30,000 a year.

00:25:00.450 --> 00:25:03.080
You cannot make ends meet here.

00:25:03.080 --> 00:25:07.170
I heard such a strange
story the other day,

00:25:07.170 --> 00:25:09.900
and I loved it
because it emphasized

00:25:09.900 --> 00:25:12.160
the nuance of hunger.

00:25:12.160 --> 00:25:16.770
It's a mom, a single
mom with three kids,

00:25:16.770 --> 00:25:20.120
and she works part-time
at an hourly job.

00:25:20.120 --> 00:25:22.380
But her eldest son
had to go to work

00:25:22.380 --> 00:25:24.670
to make ends meet
for the family.

00:25:24.670 --> 00:25:26.120
He was in high school.

00:25:26.120 --> 00:25:28.700
Now, the good news
is he graduated.

00:25:28.700 --> 00:25:31.050
I mean that's a
fantastic outcome.

00:25:31.050 --> 00:25:32.550
And bear in mind,
he was not working

00:25:32.550 --> 00:25:34.720
so he'd have money to go
to the movies and stuff

00:25:34.720 --> 00:25:35.428
with his friends.

00:25:35.428 --> 00:25:39.050
He was working to contribute
to the household income.

00:25:39.050 --> 00:25:41.720
But he couldn't go to his
high school graduation.

00:25:41.720 --> 00:25:43.920
Well, why not?

00:25:43.920 --> 00:25:47.130
Because he was afraid
to ask for the time off.

00:25:47.130 --> 00:25:48.660
He doesn't have FTO.

00:25:48.660 --> 00:25:50.420
He doesn't have benefits.

00:25:50.420 --> 00:25:53.980
And that money was too
critical to his family.

00:25:53.980 --> 00:25:57.360
And the mom when she was
telling the story, cried.

00:25:57.360 --> 00:25:59.860
And she said, I'm a
failure as a parent.

00:25:59.860 --> 00:26:01.640
I mean I'm so proud
of my son, but what

00:26:01.640 --> 00:26:04.500
should have been one of
the best days of his life

00:26:04.500 --> 00:26:08.860
was not because I can't
provide for my family.

00:26:08.860 --> 00:26:11.630
That's what hunger looks
like here in the Bay area.

00:26:11.630 --> 00:26:15.390
And the coping strategies that
people use, they're amazing,

00:26:15.390 --> 00:26:18.170
and actually, quite creative.

00:26:18.170 --> 00:26:20.730
They eat a lot of soup.

00:26:20.730 --> 00:26:22.750
They water down their milk.

00:26:22.750 --> 00:26:25.540
They eat food past
its expiration date.

00:26:25.540 --> 00:26:27.000
If they're parents,
they probably

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:29.410
skip meals so that
their kids don't

00:26:29.410 --> 00:26:32.700
have to go to school hungry.

00:26:32.700 --> 00:26:35.040
Almost half the people
we serve tell us

00:26:35.040 --> 00:26:38.160
they've traded off
educational expenses

00:26:38.160 --> 00:26:40.010
to be able to afford food.

00:26:40.010 --> 00:26:42.120
That might mean they
didn't have a backpack,

00:26:42.120 --> 00:26:44.570
they didn't have basic
stuff that their kid

00:26:44.570 --> 00:26:45.930
needed for school.

00:26:45.930 --> 00:26:49.450
It might mean they had to defer
college or take fewer courses

00:26:49.450 --> 00:26:52.520
because they couldn't afford it.

00:26:52.520 --> 00:26:55.990
So what are we doing about it?

00:26:55.990 --> 00:26:59.020
Unfortunately, we have
to be a big business.

00:26:59.020 --> 00:27:05.640
We provide the equivalent of
a million meals every week

00:27:05.640 --> 00:27:09.410
to people in Santa Clara
and San Mateo counties.

00:27:09.410 --> 00:27:12.270
We've got to be vast, we've
got to be incredibly efficient,

00:27:12.270 --> 00:27:15.930
and squeeze every dollar
as hard as we can.

00:27:15.930 --> 00:27:18.110
But what we're realizing
is that if we really

00:27:18.110 --> 00:27:20.247
want to move the
needle on local hunger,

00:27:20.247 --> 00:27:22.080
we've got to go
neighborhood by neighborhood

00:27:22.080 --> 00:27:23.240
and block by block.

00:27:23.240 --> 00:27:26.510
And we work with 330
other non-profits

00:27:26.510 --> 00:27:31.880
to try to do that, to
really have an impact.

00:27:31.880 --> 00:27:34.617
We have a lot of
strategies around schools.

00:27:34.617 --> 00:27:35.950
And I'll tell you another story.

00:27:35.950 --> 00:27:38.630
Three weeks ago, we got
a call from a principal

00:27:38.630 --> 00:27:40.255
at Fair Oaks Elementary School.

00:27:40.255 --> 00:27:41.502
It's in Redwood City.

00:27:41.502 --> 00:27:43.960
I think you guys are going to
be pretty big in Redwood City

00:27:43.960 --> 00:27:44.960
soon.

00:27:44.960 --> 00:27:47.060
He called in panic mode.

00:27:47.060 --> 00:27:52.000
He said, I have never
seen poverty like this.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:55.420
I was sent here to improve
educational outcomes.

00:27:55.420 --> 00:27:56.930
I've got to get these kids fed.

00:27:56.930 --> 00:27:58.840
There is no way
I can do anything

00:27:58.840 --> 00:28:01.260
until we address that
fundamental need.

00:28:01.260 --> 00:28:04.450
So it's so similar to
your experience overseas.

00:28:04.450 --> 00:28:06.250
And yet, this is Silicon Valley.

00:28:06.250 --> 00:28:07.460
How could this be?

00:28:07.460 --> 00:28:08.960
So of course, we're
addressing that.

00:28:08.960 --> 00:28:11.650
And we can talk later
about other strategies

00:28:11.650 --> 00:28:12.690
with other schools.

00:28:12.690 --> 00:28:14.630
It's not just public schools.

00:28:14.630 --> 00:28:16.500
We're supporting Rocketship.

00:28:16.500 --> 00:28:18.400
We're supporting
all kinds of schools

00:28:18.400 --> 00:28:18.630
throughout the Bay area--

00:28:18.630 --> 00:28:19.280
DIANE SOLINGER: Charter school.

00:28:19.280 --> 00:28:21.446
KATHY JACKSON: --a charter
school in different ways.

00:28:24.180 --> 00:28:26.500
We also don't look much
like a traditional food bank

00:28:26.500 --> 00:28:28.270
at Second Harvest.

00:28:28.270 --> 00:28:30.740
We're not about food
past its expiry date.

00:28:30.740 --> 00:28:33.530
We're not about dented
cans of SpaghettiOs.

00:28:33.530 --> 00:28:35.960
More than half of the
food we distribute

00:28:35.960 --> 00:28:37.980
is fresh fruits vegetables.

00:28:37.980 --> 00:28:43.380
We distribute milk, and eggs,
and chicken, and peanut butter,

00:28:43.380 --> 00:28:44.720
and rice, and beans.

00:28:44.720 --> 00:28:47.730
And we do it in a dignified way.

00:28:47.730 --> 00:28:49.350
So I guess at the
end of the day,

00:28:49.350 --> 00:28:52.240
I would say about
hunger here locally,

00:28:52.240 --> 00:28:54.050
it's not a supply chain problem.

00:28:54.050 --> 00:28:56.390
Even though we're
efficiency obsessed,

00:28:56.390 --> 00:28:58.500
that is not what
local hunger is.

00:28:58.500 --> 00:29:00.650
Local hunger is personal.

00:29:00.650 --> 00:29:04.520
Local hunger is really scary for
the people who experience it.

00:29:04.520 --> 00:29:06.560
Local hunger was
the little boy who,

00:29:06.560 --> 00:29:10.410
when his teacher said, "What's
your favorite food for dinner,"

00:29:10.410 --> 00:29:12.890
said, "Dinner?

00:29:12.890 --> 00:29:16.890
Is that the meal that some
families eat in the evening?

00:29:16.890 --> 00:29:19.480
My family doesn't
eat that meal."

00:29:19.480 --> 00:29:20.990
You guys, hunger is solvable.

00:29:20.990 --> 00:29:23.100
Hunger is solvable here.

00:29:23.100 --> 00:29:25.550
And we really appreciate
our partnership with Google

00:29:25.550 --> 00:29:30.090
to ensure that anyone who
needs a meal can get one.

00:29:30.090 --> 00:29:31.420
DIANE SOLINGER: Thanks, Kathy.

00:29:31.420 --> 00:29:35.270
And Suzanne, so you've
been listening to this

00:29:35.270 --> 00:29:37.410
and getting more
involved as a Googler

00:29:37.410 --> 00:29:42.430
and joining the board of the
Second Harvest Food Bank.

00:29:42.430 --> 00:29:44.250
I'd love to learn
more about your path

00:29:44.250 --> 00:29:47.382
to finding Second Harvest and
why you got so passionate--

00:29:47.382 --> 00:29:49.590
obviously, when you listen
to Kathy, you're like, OK,

00:29:49.590 --> 00:29:50.920
we're all in, right?

00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:52.024
SUZANNE: Absolutely.

00:29:52.024 --> 00:29:54.190
DIANE SOLINGER: It's certainly
a compelling mission.

00:29:54.190 --> 00:29:58.000
We know-- I keep saying,
it's just a basic need.

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:00.750
We need to make sure
that people can eat.

00:30:00.750 --> 00:30:03.850
But for you, you took a big
step in joining the board,

00:30:03.850 --> 00:30:06.590
so tell us about that
and why you chose?

00:30:06.590 --> 00:30:08.170
SUZANNE: Absolutely.

00:30:08.170 --> 00:30:11.150
So as Kathy said,
the face of hunger

00:30:11.150 --> 00:30:13.480
looks somewhat different here.

00:30:13.480 --> 00:30:16.905
So my personal experience--
or my experience with hunger

00:30:16.905 --> 00:30:18.800
has been very personal.

00:30:18.800 --> 00:30:20.810
When I was little
girl, my father

00:30:20.810 --> 00:30:23.430
owned a construction
company, and my mom

00:30:23.430 --> 00:30:26.200
helped out with that company.

00:30:26.200 --> 00:30:29.300
My brother passed away
very unexpectedly,

00:30:29.300 --> 00:30:32.400
and my father was devastated.

00:30:32.400 --> 00:30:37.830
He became addicted to drugs,
and we lost our company,

00:30:37.830 --> 00:30:41.110
we lost our home,
we lost everything.

00:30:41.110 --> 00:30:45.960
So my mother-- it was no
longer safe for us to stay.

00:30:45.960 --> 00:30:49.400
So my mother moved
us to a shelter.

00:30:49.400 --> 00:30:52.350
And that was my first
experience with food,

00:30:52.350 --> 00:30:56.400
or I guess food scarcity.

00:30:56.400 --> 00:30:59.360
I absolutely hated it.

00:30:59.360 --> 00:31:01.270
It was really scary.

00:31:01.270 --> 00:31:03.220
I missed my clothes,
and my toys,

00:31:03.220 --> 00:31:05.860
and my house, and
my friends, and not

00:31:05.860 --> 00:31:08.940
being able to decide what
snack you wanted to eat,

00:31:08.940 --> 00:31:12.320
and it was really foreign.

00:31:12.320 --> 00:31:16.100
From there, my mom tried to
get a job and she couldn't.

00:31:16.100 --> 00:31:19.320
So she took night classes
to learn shorthand

00:31:19.320 --> 00:31:21.710
to become a secretary.

00:31:21.710 --> 00:31:25.440
And during that time,
we had no income.

00:31:25.440 --> 00:31:31.160
So we received food stamps, we
received actual bags of food.

00:31:31.160 --> 00:31:35.610
And very similarly, as much
as I was thankful for it,

00:31:35.610 --> 00:31:39.190
I really hated that our
money looked different

00:31:39.190 --> 00:31:41.820
from other people's money.

00:31:41.820 --> 00:31:44.770
I became very, very
good at mental math,

00:31:44.770 --> 00:31:48.410
because it was incredibly
embarrassing to stand

00:31:48.410 --> 00:31:52.980
in line at the grocery store
and put item by item back.

00:31:52.980 --> 00:31:57.610
And it was really hard to
watch my mom get so upset when

00:31:57.610 --> 00:32:00.330
we had to do that.

00:32:00.330 --> 00:32:02.610
And so we're really
lucky, right?

00:32:02.610 --> 00:32:04.970
I mean obviously I'm
sitting here at Google.

00:32:04.970 --> 00:32:08.010
My mom was eventually
able to get a job.

00:32:08.010 --> 00:32:12.040
She worked for all of my years
growing up, two or three jobs,

00:32:12.040 --> 00:32:14.460
so that I could really
focus on my education, which

00:32:14.460 --> 00:32:17.010
is what got me here.

00:32:17.010 --> 00:32:21.200
But it's never something
that really leaves you.

00:32:21.200 --> 00:32:24.690
I mean it probably was three
years ago where I finally

00:32:24.690 --> 00:32:27.980
stopped sorting my items in my
cart at Target, like the ones

00:32:27.980 --> 00:32:31.900
I had to buy and the ones
I maybe wanted to get.

00:32:31.900 --> 00:32:35.450
And so I think the
metric that-- being

00:32:35.450 --> 00:32:38.320
at Google and data
driven-- the metric that

00:32:38.320 --> 00:32:41.070
has been so powerful
for me is one

00:32:41.070 --> 00:32:45.490
in three children in
the Bay area is hungry.

00:32:45.490 --> 00:32:48.450
And I don't know about you
guys, but my biggest problem

00:32:48.450 --> 00:32:50.350
every day is walking
past the micro kitchen

00:32:50.350 --> 00:32:52.910
and not grabbing
something to eat.

00:32:52.910 --> 00:32:58.100
And so knowing that
statistic, and being

00:32:58.100 --> 00:33:02.760
in the most innovative,
the wealthiest community

00:33:02.760 --> 00:33:05.995
in, if not the
country, the world.

00:33:05.995 --> 00:33:07.370
We have to be able
to solve this.

00:33:07.370 --> 00:33:10.090
This is unacceptable that one in
three children in our community

00:33:10.090 --> 00:33:11.020
are hungry.

00:33:11.020 --> 00:33:14.050
And so I got to
know Second Harvest,

00:33:14.050 --> 00:33:17.030
actually, our team
volunteered there, and sort of

00:33:17.030 --> 00:33:20.415
gave me a chance to see how
crazily efficient they are.

00:33:20.415 --> 00:33:22.002
I highly recommend that.

00:33:22.002 --> 00:33:23.210
It was our favorite off-site.

00:33:23.210 --> 00:33:25.490
We go back over and over again.

00:33:25.490 --> 00:33:27.920
And also, just
really meeting Kathy

00:33:27.920 --> 00:33:31.190
and meeting the organization,
they're such thought leaders.

00:33:31.190 --> 00:33:36.300
Kathy basically won the sort
of CEO of food banks nationwide

00:33:36.300 --> 00:33:37.580
of the year.

00:33:37.580 --> 00:33:39.880
And you can tell from
her stories she really

00:33:39.880 --> 00:33:41.450
delivers on that.

00:33:41.450 --> 00:33:46.420
I think the thing that has been
most inspiring to me is really,

00:33:46.420 --> 00:33:49.550
this is solvable,
particularly given

00:33:49.550 --> 00:33:51.720
the resources that we
have as a community.

00:33:51.720 --> 00:33:55.490
And so we have an opportunity
to come together and be

00:33:55.490 --> 00:33:58.905
the model for all of these
other communities in the nation

00:33:58.905 --> 00:34:03.040
and worldwide, and say we're
not OK with this anymore.

00:34:03.040 --> 00:34:04.840
We are going to fix it.

00:34:04.840 --> 00:34:09.710
And so as Diane mentioned,
the Costco extravaganza

00:34:09.710 --> 00:34:11.420
is coming up soon.

00:34:11.420 --> 00:34:12.960
It's really fun.

00:34:12.960 --> 00:34:14.020
It's really great.

00:34:14.020 --> 00:34:17.889
Volunteer with your
teams at Second Harvest.

00:34:17.889 --> 00:34:19.650
There's so many ways
to get involved.

00:34:19.650 --> 00:34:24.230
But I think we can all agree
that no one in our community

00:34:24.230 --> 00:34:25.980
deserves to go
hungry, particularly

00:34:25.980 --> 00:34:27.289
when we are so blessed.

00:34:27.289 --> 00:34:29.330
DIANE SOLINGER: When we
think about what Googlers

00:34:29.330 --> 00:34:32.270
have to offer, we
have our time, we have

00:34:32.270 --> 00:34:34.277
our financial resources,
we have our skills,

00:34:34.277 --> 00:34:35.110
we have our talents.

00:34:35.110 --> 00:34:38.474
So when you think about
some of the big ideas

00:34:38.474 --> 00:34:40.790
that maybe your organizations
want to address,

00:34:40.790 --> 00:34:44.370
let's kind of take it up to
what could Googler's skills do

00:34:44.370 --> 00:34:47.290
to come in and help
make you more efficient,

00:34:47.290 --> 00:34:50.270
get to that nobody's
hungry metric

00:34:50.270 --> 00:34:52.670
that we're trying to get to.

00:34:52.670 --> 00:34:54.429
Any ideas on how
Googlers can help,

00:34:54.429 --> 00:34:57.470
besides opening their
wallets, which they do.

00:34:57.470 --> 00:34:59.330
ROD BROOKS: Which we're
very grateful for.

00:34:59.330 --> 00:35:03.910
So one of the
things that to which

00:35:03.910 --> 00:35:07.786
we can attribute that, the
reduction in global hunger,

00:35:07.786 --> 00:35:09.410
is that many countries
around the world

00:35:09.410 --> 00:35:12.440
have actually made
this a priority.

00:35:12.440 --> 00:35:15.340
So in Brazil they've set
a goal of zero hunger.

00:35:15.340 --> 00:35:18.250
And there's the Union
of African States

00:35:18.250 --> 00:35:22.180
have actually set a goal
of ending hunger by 2025.

00:35:22.180 --> 00:35:25.700
That type of commitment
doesn't come about

00:35:25.700 --> 00:35:28.826
without awareness of the
issue and an insistence

00:35:28.826 --> 00:35:30.200
that we really
treat it that way.

00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:32.630
That we make it a priority.

00:35:32.630 --> 00:35:34.920
And I'm sure Kathy can
speak that in this country

00:35:34.920 --> 00:35:39.030
we've actually been recently
threatened with severe sort

00:35:39.030 --> 00:35:42.350
of rips in the safety net that
we have, even in this country.

00:35:42.350 --> 00:35:45.640
And in many countries, the
safety nets don't even exist.

00:35:45.640 --> 00:35:47.520
So the very first
thing I would say

00:35:47.520 --> 00:35:49.890
is that Googlers can
become aware and involved

00:35:49.890 --> 00:35:51.200
in this issue.

00:35:51.200 --> 00:35:56.210
It takes real advocacy
to make this a priority.

